30|$|All problem gamblers were {{confident}} of their gambling {{skills and knowledge}} about various casino games. They believed they had better chances of winning than their guests and other non-gaming employees. Many insisted that they had insider knowledge about different games, and had developed winning strategies to beat the system. They {{used a variety of}} strategies to enhance the chances of winnings (e.g. wearing red underwear and carrying special objects which would bring good fortune). Past studies indicate perceived insider knowledge and <b>illusion</b> <b>about</b> winnings may lead to problem gambling (e.g. Hing & Breen 2005).|$|R
